Kenya has recorded 29 new COVID-19 cases from
a sample size of 5,547 tested in the last 24 hours, marking a positivity rate
of 0.5 per cent. This brings the total number of cases
confirmed in the country to 322,669 out of the 3,327,872 tests conducted so
far. Of the cases, 20 are Kenyans while 9 are
foreigners; 15 are females and 14 are males, while the youngest is an
18-year-old and the oldest is 84 years. In terms of county distribution, Nairobi
leads with 15 cases followed by Uasin Gishu 3, Busia 2, Kisumu 2, Mombasa 2,
Kiambu 1, Migori 1, Muranga 1, Nandi 1 and Nyandarua 1. The Ministry of Health, in a statement to
newsrooms on Saturday, noted that 44 patients recovered from the disease, all who
were discharged from various health facilities countrywide. Total recoveries now stand at 303,010 of
which 250,158 are from the Home-Based Care and Isolation program, while 52,852
were discharged from various health facilities countrywide. The ministry also stated that two patients
succumbed to the virus in the last 24 hours, pushing the cumulative fatalities
to 5,633. The ministry further said 109 patients are
currently admitted in various health facilities countrywide, while 594 are
under the Home-Based Isolation and Care program. “3 patients are in the Intensive Care Unit
(ICU) and all of them are on ventilatory support. Another 22 patients are on
supplemental oxygen and all of them are in the general wards. No patient is in
the High Dependency Unit (HDU),” ,” said Health Cabinet Secretary Mutahi Kagwe. On the vaccination exercise, CS Kagwe
announced that 16,099,006 vaccines had been administered across the country as
of February 18, 2022. Of these, 7,642,960 are partially vaccinated
while those fully vaccinated are 7,334,529. “The total number of vaccines administered in
the last 24 hours is 50,826 while the total number of people fully vaccinated
in the last 24 hours is 28,505,” stated the CS. He added that 863,850 are doses administered
to those between 15 to 17 years while 240,871 are booster doses.  “The uptake of the second dose among those
who received their first dose was at 63.3%. The proportion of adults fully
vaccinated was 26.9%. The Government is working towards vaccinating a targeted
population of 27,246,033,” said Kagwe.